 "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": ". A practical guide from VCMO also describes fractional leaders as executive-level decision-makers who influence strategy and lead teams, rather than acting as task-based support ", "decorations": []}}, {"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "VCMO", "decorations": [{"type": "LINK", "linkData": {"link": {"url": "https://www.vcmo.uk/resource/what-is-fractional-leadership-a-definitive-guide", "target": "BLANK", "rel": {"nofollow": true}}}}, {"type": "UNDERLINE"}]}}, {"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": ".", "decorations": []}}], "paragraphData": {"textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "PARAGRAPH", "id": "zt0ty1106", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "The value is not just financial. Fractional leadership reduces hiring risk, shortens the time to impact, and gives businesses room to scale the function properly before making a permanent commitment.", "decorations": []}}], "paragraphData": {"textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "HEADING", "id": "where-it-fits-best", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "Where it fits best", "decorations": []}}], "headingData": {"level": 2, "textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "PARAGRAPH", "id": "qljd61109", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "Fractional leadership tends to work best when a business is at an inflection point. That might be when:", "decorations": []}}], "paragraphData": {"textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "BULLETED_LIST", "id": "2iypa1111", "nodes": [{"type": "LIST_ITEM", "id": "fnsog1112", "nodes": [{"type": "PARAGRAPH", "id": "zrp021113", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "The marketing function is underperforming but not yet large enough to justify a full-time director.", "decorations": []}}], "paragraphData": {"textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}]}, {"type": "LIST_ITEM", "id": "tzqnh1115", "nodes": [{"type": "PARAGRAPH", "id": "e9t8b1116", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "The business needs strategic leadership to align teams, but the day-to-day workload is still relatively light.", "decorations": []}}], "paragraphData": {"textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}]}, {"type": "LIST_ITEM", "id": "4nvsz1118", "nodes": [{"type": "PARAGRAPH", "id": "i7tsp1119", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "A founder is carrying too much of the digital decision-making and needs senior support without a permanent hire.", "decorations": []}}], "paragraphData": {"textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}]}, {"type": "LIST_ITEM", "id": "pmi7l1121", "nodes": [{"type": "PARAGRAPH", "id": "b1els1122", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "The company is entering a growth phase and wants to build the function properly before recruiting at full time.", "decorations": []}}], "paragraphData": {"textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}]}], "bulletedListData": {"indentation": 0}}, {"type": "PARAGRAPH", "id": "0oko31124", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "In these situations, fractional leadership acts as a bridge between where the business is now and where it needs to go next.", "decorations": []}}], "paragraphData": {"textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "HEADING", "id": "the-cost-of-hiring-too-early", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "The cost of hiring too early", "decorations": []}}], "headingData": {"level": 2, "textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "PARAGRAPH", "id": "v2zxz1127", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "Hiring full time too early often creates more pressure than progress. A senior hire may be expensive, but the real cost is in misalignment: the role is too broad, the workload is too light, or the business is not yet ready to support the level of leadership it has hired.", "decorations": []}}], "paragraphData": {"textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "PARAGRAPH", "id": "xxr471129", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "That can lead to frustration on both sides. The business expects transformation. The hire expects scope, autonomy, and scale. If neither is fully in place, the relationship can stall before it gets going.", "decorations": []}}], "paragraphData": {"textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "PARAGRAPH", "id": "mc18y1131", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "Fractional leadership avoids that trap by matching leadership capacity to actual demand. Instead of trying to force a full-time structure into an early-stage need, it lets the business build in the right order.", "decorations": []}}], "paragraphData": {"textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "HEADING", "id": "when-to-make-the-switch", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "When to make the switch", "decorations": []}}], "headingData": {"level": 2, "textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "PARAGRAPH", "id": "mtrin1134", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "Fractional leadership should usually be treated as a bridge, not a permanent state. It is the right model while the function is being built out, while priorities are still changing, and while the team is still defining what \u201cgood\u201d looks like.", "decorations": []}}], "paragraphData": {"textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "PARAGRAPH", "id": "pacft1136", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "The signal to switch to full time is usually workload. If the role is consistently more than a few days a week, and the business has enough clarity to define a full-time remit properly, that is the point where a permanent hire starts to make sense.", "decorations": []}}], "paragraphData": {"textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "PARAGRAPH", "id": "sqyax1138", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "By that stage, fractional leadership has already done part of the job. It has shaped the role, clarified the priorities, and created the conditions for a stronger full-time appointment.", "decorations": []}}], "paragraphData": {"textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "HEADING", "id": "why-it-is-often-the-smarter-choice", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "Why it is often the smarter choice", "decorations": []}}], "headingData": {"level": 2, "textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "PARAGRAPH", "id": "gwzkk1141", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "The biggest advantage of fractional leadership is flexibility with seniority. You get experienced decision-making without taking on a full-time overhead before the business is ready for it.", "decorations": []}}], "paragraphData": {"textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "PARAGRAPH", "id": "yyqkd1143", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "That makes it especially useful for companies that need to move quickly, stay lean, or avoid making a high-stakes hire too early. It is not a compromise. In many cases, it is the most commercially sensible way to access senior digital leadership.", "decorations": []}}], "paragraphData": {"textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "PARAGRAPH", "id": "rh27y1145", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "When used well, fractional leadership helps businesses make better decisions now and better hiring decisions later.", "decorations": []}}], "paragraphData": {"textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "HEADING", "id": "closing-thought", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "Closing thought", "decorations": []}}], "headingData": {"level": 2, "textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "PARAGRAPH", "id": "6bdfv1148", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "Not every business needs a full-time senior hire immediately. But many do need senior thinking, structure, and accountability before they are ready to commit to one.", "decorations": []}}], "paragraphData": {"textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "PARAGRAPH", "id": "422qg1150", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "That is where fractional leadership earns its place: it gives the business exactly what it needs, when it needs it, and only at the level it can actually use.", "decorations": []}}], "paragraphData": {"textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}], "documentStyle": {}}'::jsonb, 3, false, false, '2026-07-11T08:05:18Z');
insert into blog_posts (title, slug, excerpt, content_text, rich_content, minutes_to_read, featured, pinned, first_published_at) values ('Why Most Digital Transformations Stall at the Operations Layer', 'why-most-digital-transformations-stall-at-the-operations-layer', 'Most digital transformation programmes fail quietly — not at launch, but six months later, when the operations layer can’t keep up with what the new strategy promised. The pattern is consistent. A business invests in a new platform, a new channel, or a new strategy. The front end looks transformed. But underneath, the same manual reconciliation, the same fragmented inventory data, and the same disconnected systems are still doing the actual work — just under more pressure. According to...', 'Most digital transformation programmes fail quietly — not at launch, but six months later, when the operations layer can’t keep up with what the new strategy promised. The pattern is consistent. A business invests in a new platform, a new channel, or a new strategy. The front end looks transformed. But underneath, the same manual reconciliation, the same fragmented inventory data, and the same disconnected systems are still doing the actual work — just under more pressure. According to McKinsey, operational improvements such as inventory accuracy and supply-chain visibility can materially reduce stockouts and holding costs, which is a good reminder that transformation is only as strong as the systems behind it. Harvard Business Review has also repeatedly pointed out that digital change fails when organisations treat technology as the whole programme rather than part of a wider operating model shift. The gap nobody budgets for Strategy decks rarely account for the operational rework a transformation actually requires. Unifying inventory across channels, connecting systems that were never designed to talk to each other, retraining teams on new workflows — this is where the real cost lives, and it’s almost never where the budget is. This is why businesses often see a strong launch, then a slow drop-off in performance once the original project team moves on. The promise was digital transformation. The reality is that the business still has to run the new model every day. Research from IHL Group shows how expensive operational disconnects can become when stock accuracy and fulfilment fall behind demand. In omnichannel environments, Shopify also highlights that real-time visibility is a major driver of both conversion and customer satisfaction. Why this happens Most transformation programmes are planned around outputs, not operating conditions. Leaders define the new channel, the new workflow, or the new customer experience, but they under-specify the systems and behaviours needed to support it. That creates a familiar problem: The strategy is modern. The systems are not. The team is asked to operate both at once. In practice, the gap between the two becomes the project. That means extra manual work, slower fulfilment, more exceptions, and more pressure on staff who were never given the tools to absorb the change. What successful businesses do differently In our work with multi-channel retailers, the businesses that succeed treat operations as the first project, not an afterthought to the strategy. The ones that stall treat it as implementation detail. The difference is timing. Successful teams build the operational layer first — data, workflows, system integration, team ownership — and then roll the strategy through it. That sequencing makes the transformation real instead of theoretical. It also reduces the risk of “false finish” projects, where the website, campaign, or platform launch looks complete, but the business behind it is still catching up. The takeaway If the operational layer is not ready, transformation does not fail loudly. It just starts leaking value. That leak shows up in manual work, stock issues, slower fulfilment, poor customer experience, and frustrated teams. By the time it becomes visible in the numbers, the business has usually spent months paying for the gap. The strongest digital programmes do not just change what the business sells. They change how the business works.', '{"nodes": [{"type": "PARAGRAPH", "id": "2tgnk1295", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "Most digital transformation programmes fail quietly \u2014 not at launch, but six months later, when the operations layer can\u2019t keep up with what the new strategy promised. The pattern is consistent. A business invests in a new platform, a new channel, or a new strategy. The front end looks transformed. But underneath, the same manual reconciliation, the same fragmented inventory data, and the same disconnected systems are still doing the actual work \u2014 just under more pressure. According to ", "decorations": []}}, {"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "McKinsey", "decorations": [{"type": "LINK", "linkData": {"link": {"url": "https://www.mckinsey.com/capabilities/operations/our-insights/supply-chain-4-0-inventory-optimization", "target": "BLANK", "rel": {"nofollow": true}}}}, {"type": "UNDERLINE"}]}}, {"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": ", operational improvements such as inventory accuracy and supply-chain visibility can materially reduce stockouts and holding costs, which is a good reminder that transformation is only as strong as the systems behind it. ", "decorations": []}}, {"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "Harvard Business Review", "decorations": [{"type": "LINK", "linkData": {"link": {"url": "https://hbr.org/", "target": "BLANK", "rel": {"nofollow": true}}}}, {"type": "UNDERLINE"}]}}, {"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": " has also repeatedly pointed out that digital change fails when organisations treat technology as the whole programme rather than part of a wider operating model shift.", "decorations": []}}], "paragraphData": {"textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "HEADING", "id": "the-gap-nobody-budgets-for", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "The gap nobody budgets for", "decorations": []}}], "headingData": {"level": 2, "textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "PARAGRAPH", "id": "8udld1306", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "Strategy decks rarely account for the operational rework a transformation actually requires. Unifying inventory across channels, connecting systems that were never designed to talk to each other, retraining teams on new workflows \u2014 this is where the real cost lives, and it\u2019s almost never where the budget is.", "decorations": []}}], "paragraphData": {"textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "PARAGRAPH", "id": "yxrtb1308", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "This is why businesses often see a strong launch, then a slow drop-off in performance once the original project team moves on. The promise was digital transformation. The reality is that the business still has to run the new model every day.", "decorations": []}}], "paragraphData": {"textStyle": {"textAlignment": "AUTO"}}}, {"type": "PARAGRAPH", "id": "0jdox1310", "nodes": [{"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "Research from ", "decorations": []}}, {"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": "IHL Group", "decorations": [{"type": "LINK", "linkData": {"link": {"url": "https://www.ihlservices.com/product/retailers-and-manufacturers-out-of-stocks-overstocks-study/", "target": "BLANK", "rel": {"nofollow": true}}}}, {"type": "UNDERLINE"}]}}, {"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textData": {"text": " shows how expensive operational disconnects can become when stock accuracy and fulfilment fall behind demand. In omnichannel environments, ", "decorations": []}}, {"type": "TEXT", "id": "", "nodes": [], "textDa